Part 2

On the second night, Vikram went out to the fire. He told himself it was simply for a short walk to clear his head, the way people tell themselves small lies when they have already decided otherwise. 

The Aghori did not look up as Vikram approached the edge of the jungle. He didn't stop the regular motion of his hand. 

It was ash, Vikram saw now, as he stepped closer into the circle of firelight. The Aghori lifted a handful from a small heap beside him and let it slide slowly through his fingers, over and over, into a fire that didn't seem to need any other fuel than that dry grey dust.

"Sit down if you are going to sit," the Aghori said, his voice deep and raspy. "Standing there at the edge of the light is worse manners than sitting."

Vikram sat on a smooth stone, keeping a distance that felt safe but probably wasn't.

"You run something," the Aghori said. It was not a question.

"A company," Vikram said, looking at the embers. "My father's company."

"Your father's." The Aghori repeated the phrase the way a teacher repeats a student's mistake back to him, gently, so he can hear the error himself. "And whose is it now?"

Vikram didn't answer that. The fire crackled, a small pocket of sap popping in the dry wood.

The Aghori let another handful of grey ash slip between his fingers, falling back into the flames. "Everything you are building," he said, pointing a finger at the suitcase Vikram had left in his room, "this is what it will become. But that doesn't mean you shouldn't build it."

---

Vikram came back to the edge of the jungle on the third night. This time, he didn't need to be told to sit; he walked directly to the stone and sat down.

"What is that?" Vikram asked, nodding toward the small pile of grey dust.

"A body," the Aghori said, as if he were discussing the weather. "Somebody's body, once. It doesn't really matter whose."

Vikram watched the ash fall.

"You people in the cities are frightened of this," the Aghori said, looking at the flames. "But I sit in it. I sleep in it on some nights when the wind is cold. It stops being frightening once you understand it isn't waiting for you specially. It is just where everyone ends up."

"That is a very bleak way to live," Vikram said.

"Is it?" The Aghori looked at him for the first time properly, his eyes catching the yellow firelight in a way that made Vikram look away first. "Or is it the only honest way to live? Maybe everything else you do is just very good decoration around the same simple fact."

Vikram had no answer for that either, and the Aghori didn't seem to expect one.

---

By the fourth day, the Aghori had started appearing at the farmhouse itself during the daylight hours. He sat on the low stone wall outside Vikram's guest room as if he had always been permitted there. 

Perhaps, in Ramanna's silent accounting of the world, he had. The caretaker brought him a glass of hot tea without being asked, the way you would bring tea to an old uncle who visits too rarely to be told to stop.

"Empty," the Aghori said one afternoon, watching Vikram read through a thick stack of licensing agreements on the verandah.

"What is?" Vikram asked, looking up.

"All of it. This," he gestured with his ash-stained hand toward the papers, the farmhouse, the coffee hills, and the sky. "It will pass. You will pass. The company will pass. Even this tea in my glass will be finished in a minute, and no one will remember it was ever hot."

"Then why bother with any of it?" Vikram asked, leaning back against the stone pillar. "Why build the factories?"

"I didn't say don't bother," the Aghori said, drinking his tea slowly. "I said don't be surprised when it goes. That is a different thing entirely. A man who expects the tea to go cold still drinks it while it is hot. Only a fool sits waiting for it to stay warm forever, and calls that patience."

Vikram looked down at the licensing papers. Oddly, he found himself finishing his reading faster that afternoon, and minding the dry details less.

He didn't tell Reddy, when they spoke on the phone that evening about the land acquisition, why his voice sounded calmer than it had in months. He wasn't sure he could have explained it correctly even if he had tried.

[End of Part 2]
